{"questionId":"22116167","questionHtml":"<p>Hence find the exact area between the curve&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;the <em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math></em>-axis and the lines&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>. Give your answer in the form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mi>b</mi></math> , where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℕ</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognizing that area is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mn>0</mn><mn>6</mn></msubsup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>15</mn></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>use of log laws for their expression&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>5</mn></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>25</mn></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>ln</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mn>625</mn></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)A0M0A0</strong></em> for an unsupported final answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43775</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p>Award at most <em><strong>(M1)A1FTM0A0</strong></em> if their answer from part (a) does not include <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ln</mi></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22116167","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ1.9b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence find the exact area between the curve y=82x+3, the x-axis and the lines x=0 and x=6. Give your answer in the form a ln b , where a, b∈ℕ.","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.11—Indefinite integration, reverse chain, by substitution","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.12—Areas under a curve onto x or y axis. Volumes of revolution about x and y","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.9—Log laws"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}